# Testing with Vitest

## Structure

Tests live in `tests/` at the project root, mirroring `src/` structure:

```
tests/
  unit/
    controllers/    # Controller unit tests
    db/             # Query function tests
    middleware/     # Middleware tests
    utils/          # Utility tests
  integration/
    routes/         # Full route integration tests
  helpers/          # Shared test utilities, factories, mocks
  setup.ts          # Global test setup
```

## Naming

- Test files: `<module>.test.ts` (e.g., `habit.controller.test.ts`)
- Use `describe` blocks matching the module/function name
- Test names: `it('should <expected behavior> when <condition>')` — be specific

## Patterns

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: focused, isolated, descriptive
describe('createHabit', () => {
  it('should return 201 and the created habit when input is valid', async () => {
    const result = await createHabit(mockUserId, { name: 'Exercise' });
    expect(result).toMatchObject({ name: 'Exercise', user_id: mockUserId });
  });

  it('should throw AppError when user does not exist', async () => {
    await expect(createHabit('invalid-id', { name: 'Read' }))
      .rejects.toThrow(AppError);
  });
});
```

## Rules

- One assertion concept per test — multiple `expect` calls are fine if testing one behavior
- Use `vi.mock()` for external dependencies (db pool, bcrypt, jwt)
- Use factories in `tests/helpers/` to build test data — avoid hardcoded objects in every test
- Clean up state in `beforeEach` / `afterEach`, not between individual assertions
- Integration tests use a real test database — never mock the db layer in integration tests
- Never test implementation details — test inputs and outputs, not internal method calls
